Godard/Von Trier: Tisch School of the Arts at NYU                           Skip to content        Undergraduate Film & Television Admissions About the Program Course Offerings Summer Courses Showcase Internships Facilities Special Projects First Run & Festivals Calendar of Events News TSOA FTV Wiki Admin & Faculty Alumni Blog Facebook Twitter YouTube  home > Undergraduate Film & TV        Comparative Directors: Jean-Luc Godard/Lars Von Trier  H72.0030 Lecture & Recitation - Tier Three 4 Credits Instructor(s): Cecilia Sayad Though set apart in both time and space, the confrontational cinematic practices of Jean-Luc Godard and Lars Von Trier have in common the desire to constantly push the limits of film’s aesthetic and political potentials. A pivotal figure of the 1960’s French New Wave, Godard broke with the rules of classic cinema in order to open up film language to an infinite number of aesthetic and political possibilities. More than thirty years later, Von Trier and other Danish directors signed a manifesto (Dogme 95) that aimed at innovation through the limiting of stylistic choices. The comparative study of these two directors shows that some of the themes and stylistic traits pervading their works are better identified and understood by the investigation of the ways in which these works simultaneously intersect and diverge from each other. Among the issues examined are the controversies surrounding the figure of the film author, classic and self-reflexive techniques, genre, intertextuality, Brechtian aesthetics, the troubled relationship between Europe and the United States, and the representation of sex, women and religion. This course is cross-listed with H56.1159 (UG FILM/TV).
